$PAR SOLUTION $PAR


Let \(G\) be a group.  For any subgroup \(K\) of \(G\) and any elements
\( x, y\in G\),

$BR

(*)
\( \)
\( \)
\( \)
\( xH = yH \) if and only if  \( y^{-1}x\in H \).

$BR

Let us apply this to the case where \(G\) is the dihedral group of order
\( 2m\).
Apply (*) to
\(
  H = \langle a^{$i} \rangle
\)
and it follows that
\(
  a^{u}H = a^{g}H
\)
if and only if
\(
  a^{u - g}\in \langle a^{i} \rangle,
\)
which happens if and only if
\(
  u - g \equiv 0 \pmod{ gcd(m, i) }.
\)
Similarly,
\(
  a^{u} bH = a^{g} bH
\)
if and only if
\(
 \langle a^{i} \rangle
\)
contains
\(
  (a^{g} b)^{-1}(a^{u}b) = b a^{u-g} b = a^{g-u},
\)
so once again we arrive at the same condition, that
\(
  u - g \equiv 0 \pmod{ gcd(m, i) }.
\)

$BR

Next, take
\(
  H = \langle a^i b \rangle.
\)
Then
\(
  a^{u}H = a^{g}H
\)
if and only if
\(
  a^{u - g}\in \langle a^{i}b \rangle,
\)
which happens if and only if
\(
  u - g \equiv 0 \pmod{m}.
\)
Finally, we check that this same condition holds for
\(
  a^{u} bH = a^{g} bH
\)
as well.


